Use `Request.BodyReader` (or `Request.Body`) to stream directly to disk, bypassing the `IFormFile` memory buffer. Key steps:

**1. Disable request size limits and form buffering:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart boundary from Content-Type
    var contentType = request.ContentType ?? "";
    var boundary = GetBoundary(contentType);
    if (boundary is null)
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing multipart boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize!
        var destPath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = File.Create(destPath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);       // streams 80 KB at a time
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
})
.DisableAntiforgery()
.WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

**2. Helper to extract the boundary:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

static string? GetBoundary(string contentType)
{
    var parsed = MediaTypeHeaderValue.Parse(contentType);
    return HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(parsed.Boundary).Value;
}
```

**Why this works:**

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| Memory use | Entire file buffered | ~80 KB streaming buffer |
| 2 GB file | OOM crash | Constant memory |

**Key points:**

- `MultipartReader` reads the raw multipart stream section-by-section — nothing is buffered in memory.
- `DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute` removes the default 30 MB Kestrel cap for that endpoint.
- Don't bind `[FromForm]` or `IFormFile` — that triggers the in-memory buffering you're avoiding.
- If you're behind IIS/Nginx, raise their upload limits too (`maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`).
